ce:section.ce:para:
The trapping experiments were performed to demonstrate the active species involved in the photo-degradation of CIP using Fe-MOF@30%N-CNDs photocatalyst. For this, p-BQ (para-benzoquinone), IPA (Isopropyl alcohol), AO (Ammonium oxalate), and Silver nitrate (AgNO3) have been employed to scavenge the superoxide radicals, hydroxyl radicals, holes, and electrons, respectively. Fig. 10
                            represents the active role of reactive species in removing CIP under visible light irradiation. A significant decline in photodegradation efficiency has been observed in the presence of IPA, AgNO3, and AO. However, the presence of p-BQ has no significant effect on the overall photoactivity of photocatalyst. Thus, this study suggests that holes, electrons, and hydroxyl radicals play a major role in CIP degradation. The rate constant value k (min−1) of 61.5∗10^-4 (R2 = 0.98), 55.7∗10^-4 (R2 = 0.99), and 53.4∗10^-4 (R2 = 0.97), is obtained for IPA, AgNO3, and AO, respectively, using Fig. S19. The corresponding ROS contribution rates [68] are calculated using the equation below;

                                 Contribution rate (%) = {kobserved -kscavenger)/kobserved} ∗100
